On January 3, 2019, the President signed into law multiple bills, including the "Global Health Innovation Act of 2017," which requires the United States Agency for International Development to report on global health innovations; the designation of a United States courthouse in Durham, North Carolina; the "9/11 Memorial Act," authorizing grants for the operation and maintenance of memorials to victims of the 9/11 attacks; the "Good Accounting Obligation in Government Act," which requires Federal agencies to report on the status of certain recommendations; the "Stephen Michael Gleason Congressional Gold Medal Act," awarding a Congressional Gold Medal to Stephen Michael Gleason; the "Veterans Small Business Enhancement Act of 2018," providing veteran-owned small businesses access to surplus property; the "RBIC Advisers Relief Act of 2018," exempting investment advisers for Rural Business Investment Companies from certain registration requirements; the "Justice Against Corruption on K Street Act of 2018," requiring lobbyists to disclose certain convictions; the "Federal Personal Property Management Act of 2018," requiring Federal agencies to conduct an inventory of personal property; the "Department of Transportation Reports Harmonization Act," requiring certain reports to be made publicly available and establishing sunset dates for certain advisory councils and committees; the designation of a community-based outpatient clinic in Lake Charles, Louisiana; and the "Forever GI Bill Housing Payment Fulfillment Act of 2018," establishing a team to address issues with implementing housing benefits under the Forever GI Bill.